DATELINE: PHILADELPHIA

Occupy Philly appeals city's new permit proposal
Occupy Philadelphia protesters have appealed the city's inspiration to approve a allow for a plaza throughout the road from their modern-day encampment on the circumstance that they erect no tents and do not continue to be overnight there.
The protesters have been in a plaza next to City Hall due to the fact that early October as a assertion about what they call economic injustice, however the city says they have to leave to make way for a long-planned $50 million renovation project. Earlier this week, the metropolis supplied a one-month allow for the plaza across the street, however stated no one would be allowed to remain overnight and no tents or buildings would be allowed.
The protesters stated in a letter to the metropolis Wednesday that their demonstration at Thomas Paine Plaza would now not adversely influence public fitness and security or the herbal environment and used to be "within the ordinary recreational and other uses" of town property.
The demonstrators have also pointed to vendors who have been allowed to set up constructions for a Christmas Village at the nearby John F. Kennedy Plaza, popularly recognised as LOVE Park.
The mayor has referred to what he referred to as "serious health and security issues" at the current Occupy Philadelphia encampment, announcing conditions there are "intolerable," and town officers have said they do now not want to see a repeat of the 24-hour occupation at the new site.

